<docs>
	<doc for="DataGridCommandEventArgs.DataGridCommandEventArgs">
		<summary>
			<para>Initializes a new instance of the <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGridCommandEventArgs"/>
class.</para>
		</summary>
		<param name="item">A <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGridItem"/> that represents the selected item in the <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGrid"/>.</param>
		<param name=" commandSource">The source of the command.</param>
		<param name=" originalArgs">A <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.CommandEventArgs"/> that contains the event data.</param>
		<remarks>
			<para>Use this constructor to create and initialize a new
      instance of the <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGridCommandEventArgs"/>
      class.</para>
			<para>When an instance of <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGridCommandEventArgs"/> is created
   by a call to this constructor, the following properties are initialized to the
   specified values.</para>
			<list type="table">
				<listheader>
					<term>Property</term>
					<description>Initial Value</description>
				</listheader>
				<item>
					<term> CommandSource</term>
					<description>The value of the 
      <paramref name="commandSource"/> parameter.</description>
				</item>
				<item>
					<term> Item</term>
					<description>The value of the 
      <paramref name="item"/> parameter.</description>
				</item>
			</list>
		</remarks>
	</doc><doc for="DataGridCommandEventArgs.CommandSource">
		<summary>
			<para> Gets the source of the command.</para>
		</summary>
		<value>
			<para>The source of the command.</para>
		</value>
		<remarks>
			<para>Use the <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGridCommandEventArgs.CommandSource"/>
property to determine the command source that raised
the event. This property is commonly used to determine which command raised the
event.</para>
		</remarks>
		<example>
			<para>The following example demonstrates how to determine the source of the command
      using the <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGridCommandEventArgs.CommandSource"/> property.</para>
			<codelink SampleID="DataGridEdit" SnippetID="1"/>
		</example>
		<seealso cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGrid"/>
	</doc>
	<doc for="DataGridCommandEventArgs.Item">
		<summary>
			<para> Gets the item containing the command source in the <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGrid"/> control.</para>
		</summary>
		<value>
			<para>A <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGridItem"/> that represents the selected item in the <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGrid"/>
control.</para>
		</value>
		<remarks>
			<para>The <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGridCommandEventArgs.Item"/>
property is used to access the properties of the selected item in the <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGrid"/>
control. </para>
		</remarks>
		<example>
			<para>The following example demonstrates how to retrieve the description and price of an item in the <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGrid"/> control using the <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGridCommandEventArgs.Item"/> property.</para>
			<codelink SampleID="DataGridEdit" SnippetID="1"/>
		</example>
		<seealso cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGrid"/>
		<seealso cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGridItem"/>
	</doc>
	<doc for="DataGridCommandEventArgs">
		<summary>
			<para>Provides data for the <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGrid.CancelCommand"/>, <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGrid.DeleteCommand"/>, <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGrid.EditCommand"/>, <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGrid.ItemCommand"/>, and <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGrid.UpdateCommand"/> events of the <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGrid"/>
control. This class cannot be inherited.</para>
		</summary>
		<remarks>
			<para>The <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGrid.CancelCommand"/> event is raised when the
<see langword="Cancel"/> button for an item in the <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGrid"/> control is 
   clicked.</para>
			<para>The <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGrid.DeleteCommand"/> event is raised when the
<see langword="Delete"/> button for an item in the <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGrid"/> control is 
clicked.</para>
			<para>The <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGrid.EditCommand"/> event is raised when the
<see langword="Edit"/> button for an item in the <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGrid"/> control is 
clicked.</para>
			<para>The <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGrid.ItemCommand"/> event is raised when any
button for an item in the <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGrid"/>
control is clicked.
This allows you to programmatically test for when a specific command button
is clicked and take appropriate action. This event is commonly used to
handle custom command buttons for the <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGrid"/> control.</para>
			<para>The <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGrid.UpdateCommand"/> event is raised when the
<see langword="Update"/> button for an item in the <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGrid"/> control is 
clicked.</para>
			<para>For a list of initial property values for an instance of <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGridCommandEventArgs"/>, see the <see cref="M:System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGridCommandEventArgs.#ctor"/> constructor.</para>
			<para>For more information about handling events, see <see topic="cpconEventsOverview"/>.</para>
		</remarks>
		<example>
			<para>The following example demonstrates how to specify and code event handlers for
      the <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGrid.EditCommand"/>, <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGrid.CancelCommand"/>, and <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGrid.UpdateCommand"/> events to
      edit items in the <see cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGrid"/>
      control.</para>
			<codelink SampleID="DataGridEdit" SnippetID="1"/>
			<codelink SampleID="DataGridEdit2" SnippetID="1"/>
		</example>
		<seealso cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGridCommandEventHandler"/>
		<seealso cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGrid"/>
		<seealso cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGrid.CancelCommand"/>
		<seealso cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGrid.DeleteCommand"/>
		<seealso cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGrid.EditCommand"/>
		<seealso cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGrid.ItemCommand"/>
		<seealso cref="System.Web.UI.WebControls.DataGrid.UpdateCommand"/>
	</doc>
